Headlines.Author: Michael Calia
Headlines.Headline: FDA Grants Alexion's Soliris Orphan Status for Neuromuscular Disorder

PARAGRAPH.#text: The U.S. Food and Drug Administration has granted orphan-drug status to Alexion Pharmaceuticals Inc.'s ALXN Soliris for the treatment of a rare neuromuscular disorder. Alexion said it is enrolling participants for an international, placebo-controlled trial for patients with the refractory generalized form of the disorder, myasthenia gravis. The drug isn't yet approved anywhere for treatment of myasthenia gravis, although it has received approval for the treatment of other rare disorders. Myasthenia gravis is a debilitating neuromuscular disorder that leads to weakness in muscles, starting with the eye and progressing into other, larger muscle groups.

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The Nasdaq Composite Index continued its incredible run, soaring past
4700 for the first time and spurring traders to talk about a possible
Nasdaq 5000 soon.Driven by gains in little-known technology stocks, the index closed at
its 13th record this year, up 87.39 points, or 1.86%, to 4784.08, on record
volume of 2.2 billion shares. It was the first time Nasdaq volume, based on
4 p.m. trading, crossed two billion shares; in fact, every entry on
Nasdaq's top-10 volume list was set just this year.The Nasdaq is now up 4.5% in two days and 17.6% since the year began,
and needs to gain just 4.5% more to hit 5000. It was only this past Dec. 29
when the index crossed 4000."It looks like the Nasdaq wants to get to 5000," said Warren Epstein,
head trader at Richard A. Rosenblatt. "People predicted 5000 for the year,
and we possibly are going to get there in March."Also hitting a record was the Russell 2000 small-stock index, which
includes many of the small technology stocks that are also in the Nasdaq
composite, which includes both small and large tech names.While the market drivers included several relatively unknown names, they
came from the same group of communications, networking and biotechnology
stocks that have been in the driver's seat all year. Big gainers included
Alexion Pharmaceuticals
, a biotech
concern, Engage Technologies
, which helps
create profiles of Internet users, and Extended
Systems
, which sells equipment for mobile-communications
devices.But at a time when biotech is leading the market, Old Economy companies,
such as the huge, established drug companies, are helping hold the rest of
the market down.The Dow Jones Industrial Average, light on technology names and without
any small stocks at all, gained a marginal 0.09%, or 9.62 points, to close
at 10137.93. It is down 13.5% since hitting a record on Jan. 14, squarely
in what Wall Street calls a correction, or a drop of 10% or more from its
high. Decliners included Minnesota
Mining & Manufacturing
, Merck
, Home Depot
, International Paper
 and DuPont
.Bonds were mixed and the dollar fell."I think everybody would have liked to see more follow-through" in the
Old Economy stocks, said Ned Collins, head of trading at Daiwa Securities
America. "By the same token, if you look at Merrill Lynch
 and some of the
bellwether brokerage stocks, they really are performing very well, which I
guess indicates that people expect the market to perform. Now we have to
figure whether the New Economy is going to gain some more and pull the Old
Economy with it, because I think they have to work in tandem."Helping move communications stocks was news that SBC Communications
 and BellSouthare talking about merging
 their U.S. cell-phone operations.And Lucent Technologies
, which had
slumped 39% from its high after issuing an earnings warning in January, now
has recouped half that loss. It rose 14% Wednesday on
news that it plans to spin off
 some slower-growing operations to shareholders, creating a separate
company.Another positive factor: a sharp upswing in tax refunds, which are
coming in at a startling 20% higher rate than last year's strong rate,
according to High Frequency Economics in Valhalla, N.Y. That could fuel
consumer spending, which is bad news for those who fear an overly hot
economy, but also means more money to put into stocks.Few investors yet are talking about
economic data
 due out Friday, notably the announcement of February's employment
and pay increases. A big jump in either category would rekindle worries
about higher inflation and interest rates.But "there is a feeling out there that interest rates aren't affecting
Nasdaq stocks," Mr. Epstein noted. "I don't know if it is true, but the
feeling is that because they raise money through stock offerings and other
means, they aren't as reliant on banks for their financing."Internet stocks Wednesday continued their surge, and the Dow Jones
Internet Index closed at another record, up 9.17 points, or 2.05%, at
455.74.Outside the U.S., stocks advanced strongly in dollar terms. The Dow
Jones World Stock Index, excluding U.S. stocks, rose 4.04 points to
189.44.In major market action:Stocks gained
. On the Big Board, where 1.26 billion shares traded, 1,543 stocks
advanced and 1,495 declined.Bonds were mixed
. Although the 30-year bond fell, the 10-year Treasury note rose
6/32, or $1.875 for a $1,000 note, pushing its yield down to 6.379%.The dollar fell
. It traded at 97.28 cents to the euro and 107.18 yen to the dollar,
from 96.54 cents and 110.21 yen late Tuesday in New York.Write to
